The roots of \( P(x) \) are at \( x = 1, 2, 3, \ldots, 10 \), splitting the number line into 11 intervals: \((-∞, 1)\), \((1, 2)\), \((2, 3)\),..., \((9, 10)\), and \((10, ��)\). The sign of \( P(x) \) in each interval \((m, m+1)\) is given by \((-1)^{10 - m}\). This is because in each interval \((m, m+1)\), there are \(10 - m\) negative factors (from \(x - k\) where \(k \geq m+1\)), and each negative factor contributes a factor of \(-1\). The sign alternates starting from positive for the interval \((-∞, 1)\) (where \( m = 0 \)) and continues alternating with each subsequent interval. Specifically, the sign is positive when \(10 - m\) is even, which occurs when \(m\) is even.
